              "sample.output_text": "In Python, you can reverse a string in several ways. Here are a few common methods:\n\n### Method 1: Slicing\nYou can use slicing to reverse a string easily.\n\n```python\ns = \"hello\"\nreversed_s = s[::-1]\nprint(reversed_s)  # Output: \"olleh\"\n```\n\n### Method 2: Using the `reversed()` function\nYou can also use the built-in `reversed()` function along with `join()` to reverse a string.\n\n```python\ns = \"hello\"\nreversed_s = ''.join(reversed(s))\nprint(reversed_s)  # Output: \"olleh\"\n```\n\n### Method 3: Using a Loop\nYou can manually reverse the string using a loop.\n\n```python\ns = \"hello\"\nreversed_s = ''\nfor char in s:\n    reversed_s = char + reversed_s\nprint(reversed_s)  # Output: \"olleh\"\n```\n\n### Method 4: Using Recursion\nYou can use a recursive function to reverse a string as well.\n\n```python\ndef reverse_string(s):\n    if len(s) == 0:\n        return s\n    else:\n        return s[-1] + reverse_string(s[:-1])\n\ns = \"hello\"\nreversed_s = reverse_string(s)\nprint(reversed_s)  # Output: \"olleh\"\n```\n\nYou can choose any of these methods based on your preference or specific use case. The slicing method is the most concise and commonly used in practice.",
